trashday.model

Class CalendarEvent

  • java.lang.Object
    • trashday.model.CalendarEvent

  • public class CalendarEvent
extends Object
    Data structure for the recurring iCal events in the regular pickup schedule.

    NOTE: The calendar and its events do NOT keep associated time zone information. This keeps time zone management outside of the Calendar storage model.

    Author:
    J. Todd Baldwin
    See Also:
    iCal4j, iCal4j Javadocs, Jackson Module: Model Versioning, RFC 5545: Internet Calendaring and Scheduling Core Object Specification (iCalendar)

      • addRecurrenceWeekly

        public void addRecurrenceWeekly(DayOfWeek dow,
                                Integer interval)
        Add a weekly recurrence to this CalendarEvent.

        RRULE:FREQ=WEEKLY;BYDAY=TU RRULE:FREQ=WEEKLY;INTERVAL=1;BYDAY=TU RRULE:FREQ=WEEKLY;INTERVAL=2;BYDAY=TU

        Parameters:
        dow - DayOfWeek this recurrence will happen.
        interval - This recurrence happens every N weeks. For example, 1=weekly, 2=biweekly, etc.

        Parameters:

      • getIcalDateTime

        protected DateTime getIcalDateTime(LocalDateTime ldt)
        Generate a DateTime from a LocalDateTime.

        NOTE: Uses a ZonedDateTime as an interim step in the conversion. This is necessary because early Java date/time model was bad, then ical4j had to compensate, and then we're using the improved Java 8 date/time model. Grrr. The use of time zone as an interim step actually "cancels-out" as the ical4j DateTime actually doesn't use the time zone later.

        Parameters:
        ldt - LocalDateTime source
        Returns:
        DateTime

      • getLocalDateTime

        protected LocalDateTime getLocalDateTime(Date icalDate)
        Generate a LocalDateTime from a DateTime.

        NOTE: Uses a ZoneId.systemDefault() as an interim step in the conversion. This is necessary because early Java date/time model was bad, then ical4j had to compensate, and then we're using the improved Java 8 date/time model. Grrr. The use of time zone as an interim step actually "cancels-out" as the ical4j DateTime was actually not used anyway.

      • getRecurrencesPrintable

        @Deprecated
public Map<String,String> getRecurrencesPrintable(LocalDateTime ldtBase)
        Deprecated. 
        Get a printable form of all the ways this event recurs. For example, "every Tuesday at 7:30 AM", "every other Friday at 7:30 AM (starting this Friday at 7:30 AM)", and "on the fifteenth at noon."

        Requires LocalDateTime base to allow printing of "every other week" recurrences with starting information that states "starting this Friday" or "starting Friday after next".

        Returns recurrences as a sorted map. This allows recurrences to be sorted for display (like "every Tuesday" comes before "every Friday", "on the first" before "on the fifteenth", and weekly before biweekly recurrences). It also allows the caller to combine the recurrences from multiple CalendarEvents of the same name to be combined in a sorted order as well.

        Parameters:
        ldtBase - LocalDateTime as the base for determining if every other week starts "this" week or "next" week.
        Returns:
        TreeMap sorted map of the recurrences on this CalendarEvent
